{{Lunar January}} '''Lunar January''' (旧暦一月) is the first {{ill|Month (Calendar)|ja|月 (暦)|lt=Month|lt_ja=月}} of the year in the {{ill|Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar}} ({{ill|Lunisolar calendar|ja|太陰太陽暦}}).
Under definitions predating the {{ill|Tenpō Calendar|ja|天保暦}}, January was defined as the month that includes {{ill|Rain Water|ja|雨水}}. In the {{ill|New Calendar|ja|新暦}}, it corresponds approximately to late {{ill|January|ja|1月}} to early {{ill|March|ja|3月}}.
Another name for January is '''Mutsuki''' (睦月). For the origin of the name, see {{ill|January|ja|1月}}.
In the Eastern lunisolar calendar, the number of days in a month, known as {{ill|Large and Small|ja|大小}}, (with large months having 30 days and small months 29 days) varies from year to year. As a result, there are years when January ends on the 29th, with no January 30th. [[en:Zhengyue]] == Dates in Mutsuki == {| class="wikitable" |+ Dates in Mutsuki ! Year !! New Moon !! Last Day !! Number of Days |- | 2014 || {{ill|January 31|ja|1月31日}} || {{ill|February 28|ja|2月28日}} || 29 days |- | 2015 || {{ill|February 19|ja|2月19日}} || {{ill|March 19|ja|3月19日}} || 29 days |- | 2016 || {{ill|February 8|ja|2月8日}} || {{ill|March 8|ja|3月8日}} || 30 days |- | 2017 || {{ill|January 28|ja|1月28日}} || {{ill|February 25|ja|2月25日}} || 29 days |- | 2018 || {{ill|February 16|ja|2月16日}} || {{ill|March 16|ja|3月16日}} || 29 days |- | 2019 || {{ill|February 5|ja|2月5日}} || {{ill|March 6|ja|3月6日}} || 30 days |- | 2020 || {{ill|January 25|ja|1月25日}} || {{ill|February 23|ja|2月23日}} || 30 days |- | 2021 || {{ill|February 12|ja|2月12日}} || {{ill|March 12|ja|3月12日}} || 29 days |- | 2022 || {{ill|February 1|ja|2月1日}} || {{ill|March 2|ja|3月2日}} || 30 days |- | 2023 || {{ill|January 22|ja|1月22日}} || {{ill|February 19|ja|2月19日}} || 29 days |- | 2024 || {{ill|February 10|ja|2月10日}} || {{ill|March 9|ja|3月9日}} || 29 days |- | 2025 || {{ill|January 29|ja|1月29日}} || {{ill|February 27|ja|2月27日}} || 30 days |}
